1. File and Directory Management

ls: List directory contents.

ls -l: Detailed listing (permissions, owner, size, etc.).
ls -a: Include hidden files.
ls -lh: Human-readable file sizes.


cd <path>: Change directory (e.g., cd /var/log).

cd ..: Move up one directory.
cd ~: Go to home directory.
cd -: Return to the previous directory.


pwd: Print working directory (shows current path).
mkdir <name>: Create directory (e.g., mkdir project).

mkdir -p /path/to/nested/dir: Create parent directories as needed.


rm <file>: Remove file (e.g., rm file.txt).

rm -r <dir>: Remove directory and contents recursively.
rm -f: Force removal without prompting.


cp <source> <destination>: Copy files/directories.

cp -r <dir> <dest>: Copy directory recursively (e.g., cp -r folder1 folder2).
cp -p: Preserve file attributes (permissions, timestamps).


mv <source> <destination>: Move or rename files/directories.

mv file.txt newdir/: Move file to directory.
mv oldname.txt newname.txt: Rename file.


touch <file>: Create empty file or update timestamp (e.g., touch newfile.txt).
find <path> -name <pattern>: Search for files.

find / -name "*.log": Find all .log files.
find . -type f -mtime -7: Find files modified in the last 7 days.


locate <name>: Fast file search using a database (e.g., locate config).

Requires sudo updatedb to refresh the database.


tree: Display directory structure as a tree.

tree -a: Include hidden files.


du <path>: Disk usage of files/directories.

du -sh <dir>: Human-readable summary (e.g., du -sh /home).


ln <target> <link>: Create links.

ln -s <file> <link>: Create symbolic (soft) link (e.g., ln -s /path/to/file linkname).
ln <file> <link>: Create hard link.



2. File Viewing and Editing

cat <file>: Display file contents (e.g., cat log.txt).

cat file1 file2 > combined.txt: Concatenate files.


less <file>: View file with pagination (navigate with arrow keys, q to quit).
more <file>: Similar to less, but less interactive.
head <file>: Show first 10 lines.

head -n 5 <file>: Show first 5 lines.


tail <file>: Show last 10 lines.

tail -n 5 <file>: Show last 5 lines.
tail -f <file>: Follow file for real-time updates (e.g., logs).


nano <file>: Edit file in nano (simple text editor).

Save: Ctrl+O, Exit: Ctrl+X.


vim <file>: Edit file in vim (advanced editor).

Basic commands: i (insert), :w (save), :q (quit), :wq (save and quit).


emacs <file>: Edit file in Emacs (another powerful editor).
wc <file>: Count lines, words, or characters.

wc -l: Lines, wc -w: Words, wc -c: Bytes.


diff <file1> <file2>: Compare two files for differences.

diff -u file1 file2: Unified diff format.


patch <file> <patchfile>: Apply a diff patch to a file.

3. System Information

uname -a: Show system info (kernel version, architecture, etc.).
lsb_release -a: Display distribution-specific info (e.g., Ubuntu version).
df -h: Disk space usage in human-readable format.
free -h: Memory usage (RAM and swap).
top: Real-time process monitor.

Alternative: htop (more user-friendly, if installed).


ps: List current shell’s processes.

ps aux: List all running processes with details.


whoami: Display current username.
id: Show user and group IDs.
uptime: Show system uptime and load average.
lscpu: Display CPU information.
lsblk: List block devices (e.g., disks, partitions).
dmidecode: Hardware information (requires root).
dmesg: Show kernel log messages.

dmesg | grep error: Filter for errors.



4. File Permissions and Ownership

chmod <mode> <file>: Change file permissions.

Numeric: chmod 755 script.sh (owner: rwx, others: rx).
Symbolic: chmod u+x script.sh (add execute for user).


chown <user>:<group> <file>: Change file ownership.

chown -R user:group dir/: Recursive ownership change.


chgrp <group> <file>: Change group ownership.

chgrp -R group dir/: Recursive group change.


umask: Set default permissions for new files (e.g., umask 022).
ls -l: View file permissions, owner, and group.
getfacl <file>: Display Access Control List (ACL) permissions.
setfacl -m u:user:rwx <file>: Modify ACL permissions.

5. Process Management

ps aux: List all processes with details.
top or htop: Monitor processes interactively.
kill <PID>: Terminate process by ID (e.g., kill 1234).

kill -9 <PID>: Force kill (SIGKILL).


pkill <name>: Kill processes by name (e.g., pkill python).
killall <name>: Kill all processes with a given name.
nice -n <value> <command>: Set process priority (-19 highest, 19 lowest).
renice <value> <PID>: Change priority of running process.
jobs: List background jobs in the current shell.
bg: Send a process to the background (e.g., bg %1).
fg: Bring a background process to the foreground (e.g., fg %1).
nohup <command> &: Run command immune to hangups (e.g., nohup script.sh &).

6. Networking

ping <host>: Test connectivity (e.g., ping 8.8.8.8).
curl <URL>: Fetch data from a URL (e.g., curl https://api.example.com).

curl -O <URL>: Download file.


wget <URL>: Download files (e.g., wget https://example.com/file.tar.gz).

wget -r <URL>: Recursive download (e.g., websites).


netstat -tuln: List listening ports and services.
ss -tuln: Modern alternative to netstat.
ifconfig: Display network interfaces (older command).
ip addr: Modern alternative to ifconfig.
ip link set <interface> up/down: Enable/disable network interface.
route: Display routing table.

ip route: Modern alternative.


ssh <user@host>: Securely connect to a remote server (e.g., ssh user@192.168.1.1).
scp <file> <user@host:/path>: Securely copy files to/from a remote server.
rsync -av <source> <destination>: Sync files/directories efficiently.

rsync -av /local/ user@remote:/remote/: Remote sync.


nmap <host>: Scan network for open ports (e.g., nmap 192.168.1.1).
dig <domain>: Query DNS information.
host <domain>: Simple DNS lookup.
iptables: Configure firewall rules (e.g., iptables -L to list rules).

Alternative: ufw (simpler firewall tool, e.g., ufw allow 22).



7. Package Management

Debian/Ubuntu (apt):

sudo apt update: Update package lists.
sudo apt upgrade: Upgrade installed packages.
sudo apt install <package>: Install a package (e.g., apt install vim).
sudo apt remove <package>: Remove a package.
sudo apt autoremove: Remove unused dependencies.
apt search <keyword>: Search for packages.


Red Hat/CentOS/Fedora (yum/dnf):

sudo dnf update: Update packages.
sudo dnf install <package>: Install a package.
sudo dnf remove <package>: Remove a package.
dnf search <keyword>: Search for packages.


Arch Linux (pacman):

sudo pacman -Syu: Update system and packages.
sudo pacman -S <package>: Install a package.
sudo pacman -R <package>: Remove a package.


Snap (cross-distribution):

snap install <package>: Install a snap package.
snap remove <package>: Remove a snap package.


Flatpak (cross-distribution):

flatpak install <package>: Install a flatpak package.
flatpak uninstall <package>: Remove a flatpak package.



8. Text Processing

grep <pattern> <file>: Search text in files.

grep -r "error" /var/log: Recursive search.
grep -i: Case-insensitive search.


awk '{print $1}' <file>: Process text by fields.

Example: awk -F: '{print $1}' /etc/passwd (print usernames).


sed 's/old/new/g' <file>: Replace text.

sed -i 's/foo/bar/g' file.txt: In-place edit.


cut -d',' -f1 <file>: Extract fields from delimited files.

Example: cut -d: -f1 /etc/passwd (extract usernames).


sort <file>: Sort lines.

sort -r: Reverse order.
sort -n: Numeric sort.


uniq <file>: Remove duplicate lines (often used with sort).

sort file.txt | uniq: Remove duplicates after sorting.


tr 'a' 'A' <file>: Translate characters (e.g., lowercase to uppercase).
tee <file>: Write output to both terminal and file (e.g., ls | tee output.txt).
paste <file1> <file2>: Merge lines of files side by side.
join <file1> <file2>: Join lines of two files on a common field.

9. System Control

sudo <command>: Run command as superuser (e.g., sudo apt update).
su: Switch to another user (default: root).

su - <user>: Switch with user’s environment.


reboot: Restart the system.
shutdown -h now: Shut down immediately.
shutdown -r now: Reboot immediately.
halt: Halt the system.
init 0: Shut down (alternative).
init 6: Reboot (alternative).
passwd: Change current user’s password.

passwd <user>: Change another user’s password (requires root).


crontab -e: Edit cron jobs for scheduling tasks.
at <time>: Schedule a one-time task (e.g., at 14:00).
systemctl: Manage system services.

systemctl start <service>: Start a service (e.g., systemctl start apache2).
systemctl stop <service>: Stop a service.
systemctl enable <service>: Enable service at boot.


journalctl: View system logs.

journalctl -u <service>: Logs for a specific service.


man <command>: Show manual for a command.
info <command>: Alternative documentation system.
history: List command history.

!<number>: Re-run command by history number.



10. Compression and Archiving

tar -cvf <archive.tar> <files>: Create tar archive.

tar -zcvf <archive.tar.gz> <files>: Create compressed tar.gz.
tar -jcvf <archive.tar.bz2> <files>: Create compressed tar.bz2.


tar -xvf <archive.tar>: Extract tar archive.

tar -zxvf <archive.tar.gz>: Extract tar.gz.
tar -jxvf <archive.tar.bz2>: Extract tar.bz2.


gzip <file>: Compress file to .gz (e.g., gzip file.txt).
gunzip <file.gz>: Decompress .gz file.
bzip2 <file>: Compress file to .bz2.
bunzip2 <file.bz2>: Decompress .bz2 file.
zip -r <archive.zip> <dir>: Create zip archive.
unzip <archive.zip>: Extract zip archive.
xz <file>: Compress file to .xz.
unxz <file.xz>: Decompress .xz file.

11. User and Group Management

useradd <user>: Add a new user (e.g., useradd -m newuser to create home directory).
usermod: Modify user settings.

usermod -aG <group> <user>: Add user to a group.


userdel <user>: Delete a user (e.g., userdel -r user to remove home directory).
groupadd <group>: Create a new group.
groupdel <group>: Delete a group.
adduser: Interactive tool to add a user (more user-friendly than useradd).
passwd <user>: Change user’s password.
who: List logged-in users.
w: Show what logged-in users are doing.
last: Show recent login history.

12. Shell and Environment

echo $VARIABLE: Display environment variable (e.g., echo $PATH).
export VARIABLE=value: Set environment variable (e.g., export PATH=$PATH:/new/path).
env: List all environment variables.
alias <name>='command': Create command alias (e.g., alias ll='ls -l').
unalias <name>: Remove alias.
source <file>: Execute file in current shell (e.g., source ~/.bashrc).
. <file>: Same as source.
bash: Start a new Bash shell.
zsh: Start a Zsh shell (if installed).
set: Display all shell variables and functions.

13. Disk and Filesystem Management

fdisk -l: List disk partitions (requires root).
parted: Partition disks interactively.
mkfs.<type> <device>: Format a partition (e.g., mkfs.ext4 /dev/sdb1).
mount <device> <path>: Mount a filesystem (e.g., mount /dev/sdb1 /mnt).
umount <path>: Unmount a filesystem (e.g., umount /mnt).
fsck <device>: Check and repair filesystem (e.g., fsck /dev/sdb1).
blkid: List UUIDs and types of block devices.
dd if=<input> of=<output>: Low-level copy or backup (e.g., dd if=/dev/sda of=backup.img).

14. Miscellaneous

clear: Clear terminal screen.
date: Display or set system date/time.
cal: Display calendar (cal -y for full year).
watch <command>: Run command repeatedly (e.g., watch -n 2 date).
sleep <seconds>: Pause for a specified time (e.g., sleep 5).
tee <file>: Write output to terminal and file (e.g., ls | tee output.txt).
xargs: Pass input as arguments to a command (e.g., find . -name "*.txt" | xargs rm).
bc: Command-line calculator (e.g., echo "5+3" | bc).
which <command>: Show path to command (e.g., which python).
whereis <command>: Locate binary, source, and manual for a command.
file <file>: Identify file type (e.g., file image.jpg).

15. Scripting and Automation

bash <script.sh>: Run a Bash script.
chmod +x <script.sh>: Make script executable.
sh <script.sh>: Run shell script (alternative).
crontab -e: Schedule recurring tasks.

Example: 0 2 * * * /backup.sh (run daily at 2 AM).


at <time>: Schedule one-time task (e.g., at now + 1 hour).
watch -n <seconds> <command>: Run command periodically.

Tips for Using Commands

Piping: Use  to send output of one command to another (e.g., ls | grep txt).
Redirection:

>: Write output to file (overwrites).
>>: Append output to file.
<: Use file as input (e.g., wc -l < file.txt).


Command chaining:

&&: Run next command if previous succeeds (e.g., mkdir test && cd test).
||: Run next command if previous fails (e.g., ping 8.8.8.8 || echo "Failed").
;: Run commands sequentially (e.g., ls; pwd).


Autocompletion: Press Tab to complete commands, paths, or filenames.
History navigation:

Up/Down arrows: Cycle through command history.
!!: Repeat last command.
!<number>: Run command by history number.


Background tasks: Append & to run a command in the background (e.g., sleep 10 &).
Interrupt: Press Ctrl+C to stop a running command.
Sudo caution: Use sudo only when necessary, as it grants elevated privileges.
